            <h3>Basic guidelines for submitting new ideas</h3>

            <ul class="list-help">
                <li><strong>Make sure your idea is reasonable and necessary</strong> – if you are not sure or cannot articulate the value the improvement would drive do not submit at this time; you can always come back at a later time.</li>

                <li><strong>Search for your idea before you submit it</strong> – keep your community clean and productive by searching before you post.  Make a concerted effort to locate similar ideas and, if they are located, comment on them or suggests merge.</li>

                <li><strong>Make Title meaningful</strong> - Titles like "product improvement" offer other members little insight to what your Idea is about. Include in the tile: product name, specific functions/business processes, and a brief notion of the issue/limitation.</li>

                <li><strong>Be clear and concise</strong> - When posting an idea, put other members in the best position to judge and respond to them. Clearly state the specific issue your idea recommends addressing/enhancing. At the same time, make your post reader-friendly by keeping your idea to a few clear sentences.</li>

                <li><strong>If possible, picture it</strong> - Everybody loves colors! Make pretty pictures if you have the time. Conveying your idea visually allows community members to better envision your proposal and will lead to more promotions.</li>

                <li><strong>Be respectful</strong> - A successful community is built upon an open flow of dialogue. It is just as important to critique suggestions as it is to promote them. However, remember that we all seek a stronger more robust Aerospace environment and demeaning, insulting activity only serves to impede that effort. Always keep in mind, it's about Honeywell, not about yourself.</li>
            </ul>
            
